Cyber Digital Forensics - Key Concepts (Bullet Points)
•	Configuration Files: Non-volatile data.
•	File Deletion (Most OS): File's metadata and pointers are removed, space marked as available, data often remains until overwritten.
•	Digital Forensics Applications: Incident response, criminal investigations, civil litigation, internal investigations (All of the above).
•	Digital Forensics Report vs. Testimony: False. Reports are summaries; testimony provides significantly more detail.
•	Live System Data Acquisition: Disk-to-image copy (or logical acquisition if appropriate) is preferred. "Disk to file backup" is not a forensic best practice for live systems.
•	NIST Hash Sets: Used to quickly identify and exclude known good files (OS, applications) from analysis.
•	Unused Space in File Blocks: Slack space.
•	NIST Data Collection Steps: 
o	Develop a plan to acquire the data.
o	Acquire the data.
o	Verify the integrity of the data.
•	Analyzable Data: False. All types of data (including metadata, logs, and unallocated space) can be relevant.
•	Open Files: Volatile data.
•	TCP/IP Internet Layer Protocols (Forensic Relevance): IP (v4/v6), ICMP.
•	True/False: Digital forensics has been used to solve numerous high-profile violent crimes. True
•	True/False: When collecting forensic data from a running system, you should always attempt to collect non-volatile data first. False (Volatile data should be collected first as it's most easily lost.)
•	MAC Times: In forensic analysis, "MAC" file metadata refers to Modification, Access, and Creation times.
•	Chain of Custody: The primary purpose of maintaining a chain of custody is to ensure the integrity of evidence and prevent accusations of tampering or mishandling. It documents everyone who handled the evidence, from seizure to presentation in court.
•	Application Layer Data: Useful forensic data extracted from the Application layer of the TCP/IP model includes HTTP addresses, email content, and other application-specific data.
•	Volatile Data Collection: When collecting forensic data from a running system, you should always attempt to collect volatile data first.
•	Network Event Data: A SIEM (Security Information and Event Management) system or a log aggregator would be the best device to inspect for correlated event data across multiple network devices. (A packet sniffer captures network traffic, not aggregated events.)
•	Intrusion Attempts: A Firewall or an Intrusion Detection/Prevention System (IDS/IPS) would be the primary devices to inspect for failed penetration attempts.
•	Least Interest Application: Patch files would likely be of the least interest in a typical forensic analysis (unless the patch itself is suspected of being malicious).
•	Most Interest Application: Email is usually of great interest in a forensic analysis due to its potential for containing crucial communications.
•	Target Disk Mode: macOS (formerly Mac OS X) has a "Target Disk Mode" that facilitates creating a forensic copy of the target hard drive.
•	Order of Volatility: The order of volatility for data collection is crucial. It generally follows this sequence: CPU registers, cache, RAM, swap file, hard drive, and finally, archival storage.
•	Forensic Image: A forensic image is a bit-by-bit copy of a storage device, crucial for preserving the original evidence and allowing analysis without altering the source.
•	Hashing: Hashing (using algorithms like MD5 or SHA) is used to verify the integrity of forensic copies and ensure they haven't been altered.
•	Live Acquisition: Collecting data from a running system is called live acquisition. It's often necessary but requires careful planning to avoid data corruption.
•	Static Acquisition: Acquiring data from a powered-down system is called static acquisition. It's generally preferred when possible.
•	Anti-Forensics: Techniques used to hinder or prevent forensic investigations are called anti-forensics.
•	Legal Considerations: Forensic investigations must adhere to legal guidelines, including obtaining warrants when necessary and respecting privacy laws.

Digital Forensics Report Section & Best Practices:
•	Finding and Analysis: This section of a digital forensics report would detail the process of acquiring and analyzing digital evidence. It includes best practices like: 
o	Capturing numerous screenshots to document the state of evidence.
o	Utilizing built-in logging capabilities of forensic tools for an audit trail.
o	Exporting key data (e.g., timestamps, file hashes) into structured formats like .csv or .txt for further analysis and reporting.

Application Components:
•	Application Components: These are elements that make up a software application. Examples include: 
o	Configuration Settings: These files store how the application is set up and customized.
o	Log Files: These record events and activities within the application, crucial for investigation.
o	Supporting Files: These are necessary files (libraries, resources) that the application needs to function. Note: The OSI application layer is a networking concept, not a direct component of an application itself.

Non-Volatile Data:
•	Non-Volatile Data: Data that persists even when a system is powered off. Examples include: 
o	Operating System Files: The core files that run the OS.
o	Application Files: The files associated with software programs.
o	User-Created Data: Documents, images, videos, etc. Free space is not considered non-volatile data, it's the unused area on a storage device, which can contain remnants of previously deleted files.

Files Suitable for Forensic Analysis:
•	All file types are potentially relevant for forensic analysis. This includes documents, images, videos, executables, log files, temporary files, deleted files, and even seemingly insignificant files can hold crucial evidence.

Challenges in Computer Forensics:
•	Volume of Data: Modern storage devices can hold terabytes of data, making analysis time-consuming.
•	Encryption: Encrypted data requires decryption before it can be analyzed, which can be difficult or impossible without the key.
•	Anti-Forensics Techniques: Adversaries may use tools and methods to hide or destroy evidence.
•	Data Fragmentation: Files spread across a storage device can be challenging to reconstruct.
•	Cloud Storage: Data stored in the cloud may be subject to different jurisdictions and access limitations.
•	Rapid Technological Advancements: New technologies and devices constantly emerge, requiring forensic investigators to adapt.

Tools Used in Computer Forensics:
•	FTK Imager: For creating disk images and previewing data.
•	EnCase: A comprehensive forensic suite for data acquisition, analysis, and reporting.
•	Autopsy (using The Sleuth Kit): Open-source platform for disk imaging and analysis.
•	Volatility: For memory forensics.
•	Wireshark: For network traffic analysis.

Bit Stream Image:
•	Bit Stream Image (or Forensic Image): An exact copy of a storage device's contents, bit by bit. It's crucial because: 
o	It preserves the original evidence in its unaltered state.
o	Analysis is performed on the image, not the original device, preventing contamination.
o	It allows for multiple analyses without affecting the original evidence.

Swap Space/Page File:
•	Swap Space (Linux) / Page File (Windows): A portion of the hard drive used as virtual memory. It's relevant in forensics because: 
o	It can contain remnants of data from RAM, even after the system is shut down.
o	It may hold fragments of deleted files or passwords.

Significance in Computer Forensics (General):
•	Forensics plays a critical role in: 
o	Incident response: Investigating security breaches and data leaks.
o	Criminal investigations: Gathering evidence for prosecution.
o	Civil litigation: Supporting legal cases with digital evidence.
o	Internal investigations: Examining employee misconduct.

Hardware for Computer Forensics:
•	Forensic Workstation: A powerful computer with specialized software.
•	Write-Blocker: Prevents accidental modification of evidence during acquisition.
•	Disk Imaging Devices: Hardware for creating forensic images.
•	Storage Media: For storing forensic images and evidence.
•	Cables and Adapters: To connect various devices.


Data Recovery:
•	Chances of Recovering Data: Recovery chances depend on factors like: 
o	Time since deletion.
o	How the data was deleted (e.g., simple delete vs. secure erase).
o	Whether the space has been overwritten.
o	Type of storage device.
•	Challenges of Recovering Data: 
o	Overwriting: New data written to the same location makes recovery difficult.
o	Physical Damage: Damaged hard drives may require specialized recovery services.
o	Data Fragmentation: Reassembling fragmented files can be complex.
o	Secure Erase: Methods designed to completely wipe data make recovery nearly impossible.






 
