File Types
File Types in Cyber Digital Forensics:
•	Data Files: Encompass a wide range of user-created or system-generated files. Examples include documents (.doc, .docx, .pdf), images (.jpg, .png), videos (.mp4, .avi), audio files (.mp3, .wav), spreadsheets (.xls, .xlsx), databases (.db, .sqlite), and configuration files. These files often contain crucial evidence like timestamps, author information, and content relevant to an investigation.
•	Network Data: This category includes captured network traffic (e.g., PCAP files from Wireshark), firewall logs, router logs, DNS logs, intrusion detection/prevention system (IDS/IPS) alerts, and proxy server logs. Network data can reveal communication patterns, IP addresses, ports used, protocols, and potentially malicious activity.
•	Operating System Data: This is critical for understanding system events. Examples include event logs (Windows event logs, Linux syslog), registry entries (Windows), system logs, process lists, user accounts, file system metadata (timestamps, permissions), and swap files. OS data can provide insights into user activity, malware execution, and system changes.
•	Application Data: This includes data specific to applications. Examples are browser history (Chrome, Firefox, Edge), email data (Outlook, Thunderbird), chat logs, social media data, and data from specialized software. Application data helps reconstruct user actions within specific applications.
•	Executable Files: While technically data files, executables (.exe, .dmg, scripts) deserve a separate mention due to their potential to cause harm. Forensic analysis of executables can reveal their functionality, associated malware, and potential impact.
•	Deleted Files: While not readily accessible, deleted files are often recoverable and can contain vital evidence. Forensic tools and techniques are used to recover these files.
•	Memory Dumps: These files capture the contents of a computer's RAM at a specific point in time. They can contain valuable information about running processes, malware in memory, and sensitive data.


